## Authentication

The simplest setup is the **cleura CLI**: run `cleura login` once ‚Äî it handles the password and
two-factor authentication ‚Äî and the provider uses those credentials automatically, so the provider
block only needs `cloud`, `region`, and `project_id`.

Credentials resolve in precedence order; the CLI is the automatic fallback, so explicit
configuration and environment variables always override it:

1. **Provider configuration** ‚Äî the `username` / `token` attributes.
2. **Environment variables** ‚Äî `CLEURA_API_USERNAME` / `CLEURA_API_TOKEN` (and `CLEURA_API_URL`
   for private clouds).
3. **The cleura CLI** ‚Äî the default. With the [`cleura` CLI](https://github.com/cleura/cleura-cli)
   installed and logged in (`cleura login`), the provider reads its credentials automatically. Pin
   a specific CLI profile with the `profile` attribute, or disable the fallback with
   `use_cli = false`.

Only credentials come from the CLI; `region` and `project_id` are always taken from the provider
configuration or environment. Cleura tokens are short-lived ‚Äî if a plan fails with an
authentication error, run `cleura login` again.

~> **Warning:** An API token grants access to your Cleura account ‚Äî treat it like a password and
never commit it. The `token` attribute is stored as sensitive, but `cleura login` and the
environment variables keep it out of your configuration and state entirely.

